'''Charles Henry Dietrich''' (November 26, 1853{{spaced ndash}}April 10, 1924) was the [[List of Governors of Nebraska|11th]] [[Governor of Nebraska|Governor]] of [[Nebraska]].

He was born in [[Aurora, Illinois]]. His education was attained in the public schools of his native state and he quit at the age of twelve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles Henry Dietrich|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rWkP0DM_upwC&pg=PA92&lpg=PA92&dq=nebraska+governor+Robert+Wilkinson+Furnas&source=bl&ots=n5zrZY7rsp&sig=tHM_nvIw7QtKf5cOHDFSzN3KfcQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lUxVUOGIHsm_2QXe-oDIBg&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=nebraska%20governor%20Robert%20Wilkinson%20Furnas&f=false|publisher=The Encyclopedia of Nebraska|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> 

Dietrich was married twice. His first wife, Elizabeth Slaker, died in 1887. After Elizabeth's death, he married [[Margretta Dietrich|Margretta Stewart Shaw]] in 1909.

==Career==
Dietrich was employed as a clerk in a hardware store in [[St. Joseph, Missouri]]. He moved to [[Chicago, Illinois]] and engaged in the hardware business. He moved to [[Deadwood, South Dakota|Deadwood]], [[Dakota Territory]] (now [[South Dakota]]), in 1875 and engaged in mercantile pursuits, delivering goods on pack animals through the [[Black Hills]]. He then located and owned the ‘Aurora’ mine. 

Dietrich settled in [[Hastings, Nebraska]], in 1878 and engaged in mercantile pursuits and in banking. Dietrich founded the German National Bank at Hastings and served aw the president of the bank from 1887 to 1905.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles Henry Dietrich|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_nebraska/col2-content/main-content-list/title_dietrich_charles.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> He became the president of the Hastings Board of Trade.<ref>[http://www.nebraskahistory.org/lib-arch/research/public/state_governors/dietrich.pdf Gov. Charles Dietrich papers] at the [[Nebraska State Historical Society]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-09.</ref>

Elected in 1900, Dietrich served as [[Governor of Nebraska]] from January 3, 1901 to May 1, 1901. Having won the election to fill the vacancy caused by the death of [[Monroe L. Hayward]] in the United States Senate, he resigned his governorship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles Henry Dietrick|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rWkP0DM_upwC&pg=PA92&lpg=PA92&dq=nebraska+governor+Robert+Wilkinson+Furnas&source=bl&ots=n5zrZY7rsp&sig=tHM_nvIw7QtKf5cOHDFSzN3KfcQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lUxVUOGIHsm_2QXe-oDIBg&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=nebraska%20governor%20Robert%20Wilkinson%20Furnas&f=false|publisher=The Encyclopedia of Nebraska|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>  

His tenure in the Senate lasted from March 28, 1901, to March 4, 1905, and he served as a pro-[[imperialism|imperialist]] on the [[Lodge Committee]] investigating [[war crimes]] during the [[Philippine-American War]]. He did not run for reelection in 1904.

==Death==
Dietrich retired in 1905 and died in Hastings, Nebraska. He is interred at Parkview Cemetery, Hastings, Adams County, Nebraska USA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles H. Dietrich|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=7262369|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> 

